\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
I was born a War Baby, 1942, in a little place called Neston, in Cheshire, not where my parents were living, but where the local Nursing Home had been evacuated to. So I was born in a Nursing Home not far from Wallasey, which is where my parents lived, an
d
 we stayed in Wallasey until I was about four, and that was close to where my maternal grandparents lived. And then my father got a job in Staffordshire, which was his home area, and so we moved to Leek, which is a small Staffordshire moorlands town where
 my paternal grandparents and uncle and aunt were living, and lived there for four more years. And then my father, who was a journalist, got a job with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 Birmingham Post and Mail}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
, and we moved to Birmingham, so I spent my latter part of my primary schooli
ng and all of my secondary was in Birmingham. And then at 18, I came to London to start studying, and basically have been based in London ever since, although lots of travelling, obviously, in between whiles. 
