\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2915881 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
I knew - all of my grandparents were very much part of my childhood, and particularly my maternal grandfather, I think, was a very important influence. I should say that both families were - they kind of struggled to make it into th
e upper working-class/lower middle-class, so I think class certainly comes into some of what affected me and then }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2915881 a little bit of class mobility.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 But also the fact that - I guess I was a child of Empire, and there were so many members of my family who\rquote d travelled very widely \endash 
 not because they were well-to-do and doing the Grand Tour, but because they had been soldiers or they were migrants. So, for example, my maternal grandmother was born in Australia because her family had migrated there, presumably bec
ause of poverty, although they did eventually come back. But there remained an Australian branch, and people would appear from time to time from Australia and other family members would go and visit in Australia. And then my mother\rquote 
s older brother, who had travelled a lot during the War \endash  he\rquote d been in Ethiopia, for example, in the Second World War \endash 
 he migrated to South Africa when the War ended, and he came back and got married, they went to live in South Africa. So that they\rquote d come on visits, or they\rquote d se
nd photographs, and bring objects. So I always remember all of these houses having lots of objects which were from somewhere else - you know, Indian: both my paternal grandfather and his younger son had been in India \endash 
 he in the First World War, and my uncle just after the Second World War. So the idea of travelling to places that were very far away didn\rquote t seem at all strange. In fact, it was quite enticing. So I guess I got the travel bug early! (LAUGHS)
