s there on weekends, and I think they were all thinking, \'93What\rquote s going to come out of all of this?\'94 (LAUGHS) We\rquote 
re all going to disappear off to far-flung corners of the earth! But most of the relationships eventually fizzled out, and my own relationship fizzled out after about a year at university. There\rquote 
s so many other things going on, and so many other pebbles on the beach! But my parents never said \'85 you know \'85 and they actually liked him. I mean, he was a very likeable person, so they never said, \'93You can\rquote t \'85\'94
 Only the cleaning woman, I remember, she saw me with him once and she said to me afterwards, \'93What\rquote s the matter with you? Can\rquote t you get a white fellow?\'94
 And I was really angry and upset and all the rest of it. But anyway, that was the way it was. S
o my parents were pretty - considering their backgrounds, I think they were remarkably open-minded, and when, in fact, in the end I married somebody who was Jewish, they didn\rquote 
t turn a hair! (LAUGHS) I guess they were pretty inured by that time! (LAUGHS)
