No, no, no, no, although obviously I\rquote d had to present my credentials, and they knew I was there and all the rest of it. So I guess I\rquote d been there for about a month, and was still very much feeling my feet, when Smith declared UDI, and Tanza
nia broke off relations with Britain, diplomatic relations, with Britain, and I can\rquote 
t quite remember what the sequence was, but what I do remember was that a meeting of the village was called, that I went to. There was in every village a Government Officer
 posted, who was a paid Government official, who was occasionally from that village, but usually not, and this guy was not from Mafia, and so he explained what all of this meant \endash 
 that the white regime in Rhodesia had declared unilateral independence, and that Tanzania supported the black majority \endash 
 and, of course, Tanzania did become a front line state in terms of its support for both the majority rule in what became Zimbabwe, and also in terms of South Africa. So he explained all of this, and then he explained that they\rquote 
d broken diplomatic relations, and then he said, \'93And it\rquote s all because of people like her\'94 \endash  pointing to me, sitting at the back. And I thought, \'93Oh, goodness! This is the end of my fieldwork! I\rquote m going to have to leave\'94
. But what happened after the meeting was that a large number of people came up to me and said, \'93That man has no manners. You\rquote re our guest. And we\rquote re - don\rquote t take any notice of what he said. You stay here and do your work.\'94
 It was just incredibly reassuring. And I think part of it was that kind of Swahili hospitality as in, \'93You\rquote re our guest, and we\rquote re responsible for you\'94
, which is amazing. Wonderful! And partly, as I realised later, when I went back. I was 23 and I was single. I had no children, no husband. I was a child in 
their eyes. They saw me as a child who needed protection, and also was totally harmless. I mean, how could a woman who was so young, she didn\rquote t have a husband and children, she\rquote d got to be harmless hadn\rquote 
t she! And so anyway, it kind of passed over, and UDI stayed a problem for a long time, but it didn\rquote t really have any effect on me or my relations in the village, thank goodness.
