Okay. Well the state of studies of kinship and descent in Africa, at that time, had been profoundly influenced by the work that Evans-Pritchard did in the southern 
Sudan, on the Nuer, the famous Nuer, and a bit later that Meyer Fortes did in West Africa. And what they had found in these societies were these bounded, lineal, unilineal descent groups which had all sorts of implications in terms of territory, land righ
t
s, marriage, and the way politics functioned. So because these books became the kind of classics, so everybody went around looking for these kind of set ups in whatever bit of Africa, sub-Saharan Africa, they were working in, and indeed, in some areas the
se models \endash  because they were models, essentially \endash  worked very well and did help to make sense of what was going on, in other places they didn\rquote 
t. Fortunately, Phil Gulliver, my supervisor, had worked among one group in Tanzania that had absolutely nothing like this, and so he\rquote d been much more interested in network theory. He\rquote 
d actually published a book, his study of the Ndendeuli about how kinship can work without these unilineal descent groups. So the evidence from the coast of East Africa was confused, be
cause there did appear to be corporate groups that held land, but they didn\rquote t appear to be unilineal \endash  in other words, they weren\rquote 
t either patrilineal through the father, or matrilineal through the mother, but they appeared to be both. So that was what I w
as trying to make sense of. And what I did discover is that there are these large descent groups in which you get membership through both your father and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8913942 
 your mother, which are called \lquote Koo\rquote  \lquote Makoo\rquote  or \lquote Ukoo\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
 (singular), in some areas, but only in those areas where the old land tenure systems still persist. And they\rquote 
d more or less disappeared. So that, for example, when I first was there, they were very important in northern Mafia, and John Middleton, who\rquote d worked a little bit earlier than me, in Zanzibar, f
ound them in the more remote parts of Zanzibar, but in the areas that were closer to the towns, or where there had been a plantation economy, that had disappeared. So it depended on location really, to a large extent.
