\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid4602590 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab Well, I worked it out by taking people\rquote s genealogies initially, and then by doing \endash  I was interested
 in land and land tenure, so I spent an awful lot of time traipsing around miles and miles of bush land. Because in northern Mafia they had, at that time, a system of shifting cultivation, that was a rotation of about seven years, where they would move fr
om one area to another, because the soils are very thin, in most of sub-Saharan Africa you\rquote ve got very thin soils, and so you can\rquote t keep on and on and on, unless you can use some form of fertiliser, you just can\rquote 
t keep on using the same piece of land. And t
hen I began to realise that there was a connection, that there were actually, in that village, there were six large named groups to which membership could be obtained through mother or father, and that they also owned large tracts of bush land, and that s
ome of them were tied in with spirit possession cults. So it was quite a com}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4602590 plicated thing to work through.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 Then I realised that there were certain people who were the kind of guardians of the genealogies of these groups. I could show you - I\rquote ve got six ch
arts in there, which are the charts of the groups as they were in that period in the mid-1960s. And the biggest one, you couldn\rquote 
t open it out, it would go beyond the length of this room. And so I went to talk to each of the elders of these groups, to check, because what I\rquote 
d got were, some of them were quite big genealogies, they would be maybe four, sometimes five, generations, but these were even longer, and, therefore, broader. And they agreed. But I didn\rquote t do that until nearly the end, when people knew m
e and trusted me. And so you could plot everybody in the village on to at least one of these, and many people had multiple membership because if the parents had come from different groups, or the grandparents, then they would have multiple membership of t
hese groups.
