\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
Well, the children of any marriage would still retain rights in the birth parents. In fact, I remember when a relative of mine got divorced, and things were very sticky, I wrote a letter to the husband, the in-law husband, and said to him, \'93I think it
\rquote s a good idea to do what the Swahili do, because the Swahili always say that being an in-law never ends\'94. So even if there\rquote s a divorce, that relationship continues, and you still maintain \endash  insofar as you can \endash 
 a civilised relationship, and, of course, you have links through the children of any marriage, so it doesn\rquote t make that much of a difference really.
