\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
Well, when I asked them, they did. But the other thing is that they would be called on - there\rquote s a ritual where you go to the grave, at least once, there\rquote 
s certainly one occasion, there may be more than one in the year. You go to the graves of the ancestors, and you make an offering. It\rquote s an interesting event, because it\rquote 
s partly Islamic and partly not. But anyway, you remember the ancestors, and you honour them, and you make a religious offering, and sometimes there\rquote s a Koranic reading, but in doing th
is, you need somebody who knows the genealogies really well, and remembers who these graves belong to, because these are not graves that have people\rquote s names on them, they\rquote 
re just headstones. And so these are the kind of people who would be called on on an occasion like that. They would be called on when there were disputes about land. \'93Did X have the right to use the land of Y group?\'94 \'93
Was he or she, were they members properly, or had they kind of tried to slide their way in somehow or other, perhaps through being an in-law?\'94
 And so these people would be consulted. And they told me that they would try to choose people to pass the knowledge on to, so that there would always be somebody, so it wouldn\rquote t die with an old man. They were usually men that I talked t
o, although some women also had this sort of knowledge. Yeah.
