 where I would try, most days I wrote something. Occasionally I must have skipped, I guess. But in addition to that \endash  this was not the days of computers and e-mail \endash 
 and so I religiously, at least once a week, wrote to my parents in some detail, and the letters to my parents are interesting, because first of all I didn\rquote t want to wo
rry them, so I would never tell them if I was feeling down or whatever, but I also had to explain things to them, because they weren\rquote t anthropologists, they\rquote 
d never been to Africa. So letters to them are very different than the letters I wrote to Lionel, w
hich I did probably twice or three times a week, where I wrote as one anthropologist to another. And then I was also in letter contact with my two friends, Caroline and Janet \endash  the one in West Africa and the one in Kenya \endash 
 and I still have a collection of their letters, and my letters to them. No. I don\rquote t have, this is the pity, which is I don\rquote t always have copies of my letters, and the letters that I sent to Lionel, he threw away, at one stage, as in, \'93I
\rquote ve got to get rid of all this junk!\'94 (LAUGHS) Which is really a pity, but my parents kept my letters, so I have my letters to them as well as theirs to me, and I have Lionel\rquote 
s letters to me, commenting on things I must have said, so I can reconstruct some of it. So there\rquote s all that. And then I had to write a report every three months to my supervisor, so I\rquote 
ve got those. And then when I got back, I had to give these three seminar papers, and again, I\rquote ve got those.
