\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
Okay. So to get back to what I was doing. Well, I stayed on Mafia for 18 months, a
nd I spent a year in one village, which is called Kanga, in the north, and I visited the neighbouring village five miles away, called Bweni, very frequently, and went to lots of rituals there. And I spent a month living in another neighbouring village to 
the south-east, called Banja. And then, partly at my supervisor\rquote s suggestion, he said, \'93Oh, typicality, you\rquote ve got to find out how typical your village is\'94
. So I moved to [Baleni] a village in central Mafia, which I have to confess I never really came to grips with. The villages in the north are fairly concentrated. It\rquote 
s quite a big area, but you can get around. This one in the southern villages, because this is the area which was very influenced by plantation economies \endash  Arab, Indian, European \endash  they\rquote re ver
y dispersed, it was very hard to kind of get a grasp on things. There weren\rquote t the same corporate land-holding descent groups, there wasn\rquote 
t any bush land, and the spirit possession cults were different. So although I was there for three months, and I worked very hard, and did my best, I never quite fell in love with it. And every time I\rquote d go back to Kanga, they\rquote 
d look at me and say, \'93Oh, my God! Look how she\rquote s got thin!\'94 \'93Oh! They\rquote re not feeding you properly\'94. \'93Is it the witchcraft down there?\'94 You know, \'93What\rquote s going on?\'94
 So when I came to write my Ph.D. thesis, I think I felt that I really knew most, obviously, about the village I\rquote d spent the most time in, and I had some comparative data, but because I wanted to write about the kinship and descent system, I
 really had to focus on one fairly banded area in order to have something that I could get a handle on, and not kind of disappear off into. That\rquote s not how I\rquote 
ve necessarily worked since then, but at that time, it was a village study. It was. Yeah. I won\rquote t pretend otherwise.
