Well, the book came out much later, because what happened was that when I got back from Tanzania, we got married, and we bought a house in Finchley \endash  just across the tracks from where we live now \endash 
 and Lionel, my husband, as he was then, his specialism was Nepal. So he\rquote d done his Ph.D. fieldwork in Nepal, and there was a big Himalayan project directed by the then head of the SOAS Anthropology Department \endash 
 Christoph von Fuerer-Haimendorf, who was the pioneer of Himalayan anthropology. So he said to me, \'93We\rquote ve got this link with Cornell, and we\rquote ve got quite a lot of money, and Lionel is due to go and have another field trip\'94
. Because his appointment at SOAS was lecturer, at the beginning - Lecturer in South Asian Anthropology \endash  so he couldn\rquote t do what he always had wanted to do, because he\rquote d originally wanted to be an Africanist, but he couldn\rquote 
t get the funding to go to Africa, and he never got the chance to go and work in Africa, because that was his title at SOAS, and that was what he had to stick with. So he was due to go back to Nepal, and so Christoph said, \'93Let\rquote 
s find - you find a project too, and you can go together\'94. So I got - I suppose it wa
s like a post-doc really, so I stayed on at SOAS in a new guise, and the year that I was writing my Ph.D. thesis on Mafia, I was learning Nepali, and trying to do a bit of reading about South Asia. [But] I have to say, I arrived in Nepal at the end of 196
8, with not very fluent Nepali, and not a great deal of knowledge about South Asia. You know, I didn\rquote t know the literature intimately, I\rquote 
d read a few things, there were classics that everybody read, but not like I knew the literature on Africa, obviously. 
