\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
So, in 1969, I think it was, you went to Nepal?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
We actually went at the end of 1968, and we went via India, so we stayed in Delhi, where we bought our supplies, because, in those days, you couldn\rquote 
t get much in Nepal, so we bought bits and pieces that we needed, in Delhi. And then we flew to Kathmandu, and stayed in Kathmandu for a little while in a German
-run hostel for visiting academics - well, guest house, it was. And then we set off for our destination, which was a small town, a district capital called Dailekh, which is in the far western hills of Nepal, and to get there you had to take a plane from K
athmandu to one}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2832346  of the valleys, what\rquote s called \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 The Inner Terai}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2832346 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 , because Nepal is long and thin, and the bottom part is all lowland flat, but there are some low valleys over the first range of hills. So this valley was called Su}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2832346 rkhet, so we flew there, and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16334446  and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042  then we walked for two and a half days into the hills, to reach this town called Dailekh. I mean, we were not in A1 fit shape, so it would have taken us less time later on, but it
\rquote s quite a long \'85 you\rquote ve got to get up a lekh (?? \endash  sp.) \endash  that\rquote s a ridge of about 9,000 ft \endash 
 and you sleep there the first night, and then you come down the other side of the ridge, and then you go up another smaller ridge, to about 5,000 ft, which is where Dailekh is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
Did you have porters to carry your things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
Yes. We had, we got porters in Surkhet, and I actually found that first walk really difficult, because when I was in Delhi I\rquote d had dysentery, a very bad case, I thought I was going to die, and so I was still quite - I\rquote 
d recovered from that, but I was prett
y weak. And fortunately, we met somebody who had a pony, who was going the same way, and he was very kind, and so he let me use his pony for a few hours, so that helped. So I arrived in Dailekh pretty wiped, really! And this was a small district town on t
he top of a ridge, a government post where there would be a police post and a little clinic and a school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
What about the official situation? I mean, was it again as when you were in Tanzania, that you had to have the \'85?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
Yes. You had to have, oh yes, you\rquote 
d have to have all the correct permission. I remember we spent some time in Kathmandu going around government offices and getting all the requisite bits of paper, and then we had to present ourselves to the local district bigwigs and say who we w
ere, and all the rest of it. But they didn\rquote t give us any problems. Actually, Lionel\rquote s study, that time \endash  he\rquote 
d worked in East Nepal before for his Ph.D. research - but this one was in West Nepal, was a study of a district capital, so he actually ended up interviewing all these people and working with them, so he got to know them quite well, whereas what we
\rquote d decided was that I was not going to work in the district capital. We didn\rquote t want to work together, I was going to do a completely separate project, so I
 worked in a village which was about two miles away, and I had a house there, or rooms in a house, it wasn\rquote t a whole house, but I didn\rquote 
t stay there overnight, usually I would come back to the house we shared together in the district capital. So I did a lot of walking, I got very fit! (LAUGHS)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
What was the role of this Kathmandu Centre of Nepal Research?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab Yes, that was \'85
 it was called Thyssen House, and it was with money from the Thyssen Foundation. Well, they ran it for mainly German visiting ac
ademics but other people could ask to be accommodated, and if they had space they would put you in there. So it was very pleasant, it was very nicely run. And there were quite a few Germans, well, I suppose we encountered a lot of them because we stayed t
h
ere several times, but there were several German projects. There was a big restoration project, maybe under UNESCO auspices. In the Kathmandu Valley there was this wonderful urban civilisation, Newari civilisation, with very beautiful architecture and ama
zing town planning, including these elaborately carved windows and grilles and doorways, so there were some Germans who were working on that, and then there were other anthropologists who were working in various places. And then occasionally there\rquote 
d be mountaineers passing through, who looked down their noses at us, who were only working at 5,000 ft \endash  that was very pathetic in their terms! And would ask us how far up we\rquote d been, and we\rquote d say, \'93Well, 10 \'85\'94
 well, that was beyond the pale, you know, if you hadn\rquote t been up Everest at least once! So it was a bit of a mish-mash of people. We met the MacFarlanes there, that was the first time we met Alan MacFarlane, actually, who was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
He was researching at the same time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab He
 was, yes. And he already had a Ph.D. in history, and had published the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 Witchcraft in Tudor and Stuart England}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042  book, and then he, because of his reading in witchcraft, he read a lot of anthropology for that, and he got really interested in anthropology, so
 he decided he wanted to acquire a Ph.D. in anthropology as well, so he chose a village among a people called the Gurung, which is near Pokhara, which is the second town of Nepal, and he and his then wife were there for a year, so we\rquote 
d meet occasionally at Thyssen House. I think we met a couple of times in between this and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
So could you talk about the fieldwork you did in Duari?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1015086 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab Yeah. Well, this was a mixed caste village. Some were Brahmins of one kind or another, and they owned most of the land, and then there wer}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15600728 e a lot of what are now called \lquote Dalits\rquote , and were then called either \lquote untouchables\rquote  or \lquote Harijans\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 , who had lost a lot of their land to the higher castes. So in other words, these were caste Hindus, they were not like the people th
at Lionel had worked with, or where Alan MacFarlane was wo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15600728 rking, who were more so-called \lquote tribal peoples\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042  with different facial features and a rather different sort of culture, and sometimes their own language, so they spoke Nepali which is a Sanskritic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12070663  language quite close to Hindi.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
I got interested in land and land tenure, and the way this whole process of movement of land away from a much more egalitarian distribution system to one where land was being increasingly concentrated in the hands of the highe
r castes and why this was happening, and all the kind of changes that were taking place in this village as a result of the wider changes in Nepal. So it was very much a book about social change, and seeing this village as part of a much wider series of en
tities \endash  the districts, the region, Nepal itself as a whole. I had to have a research assistant, because my Nepali wasn\rquote t good enough, and, of course, it didn\rquote 
t improve as rapidly as I would have liked, because I was there with my husband and so we spoke English in the evenings and on our day a week off, again, we\rquote 
d talk English. I mean, it did improve. By the end of the year I could hold my own pretty well, but I was never as flue}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12070663 nt as Lionel was.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 Of course, that was the other somewhat galling thing, which is from a situation in East Africa where I\rquote d been extremely fluent and dealt with everyth}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451632 ing myself, I was put into the \lquote wife\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
 category, and that was harder to deal with because I was very dependent on [him], he did speak very fluent Nepali, and he was an old Nepal hand by that time, and I was a complete novice. So it wasn\rquote 
t always that easy. And the living conditions were quite difficult. I mean, it was physically very arduous because the village where I worked lay - there was about a 2,000 ft. drop and p
eople were scattered over the first 1500 ft., so I had to do a lot of walking up and down, and then the fields, most of them were below that still, so there was a lot of hard walking and climbing, and up a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11612901 nd down and all the rest of it.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 The first research assistant I had, he wasn\rquote 
t too bad \endash  Hari his name was. He was from Surkhet and so he knew about hills and all the rest of it. I can\rquote t remember why he left, he needed to leave for some reason, half way through, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid15738587 and we had been in Kathmandu and we got somebody in Kathmandu who, I think, had a university degree, and he was a complete disaster! He couldn\rquote t walk, he didn\rquote 
t know how to do hill walking, and he really hated it. And then we discovered he was drinking heavily. Anyway, we had to get rid of him.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042  And 
then I worked, sometimes, with \endash  Lionel had two research assistants \endash  and I worked, sometimes, with one of them. But I was able, by this time, fortunately, I could manage much more on my own, so it wasn\rquote 
t too disastrous. But it was obviously a very very different situation being in the field with a partner than being on my own, and being in a field where I wasn\rquote t familiar - as I had been in East Africa \endash  and where I wasn\rquote t as fami}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451632 liar as my partner was.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
But the other complicating thing was that Lionel got 
very ill in the middle. We found out later it was a kidney stone, and so he was in agonising pain, and there was no medication. But, fortunately, there was some kind of radio contact with Kathmandu, that worked occasionally, so I spent a week kind of runn
ing between our house and trying to keep Lionel calm, and get him to relax against these waves of pain, and this telegraph office, or whatever it was. And finally, finally, somebody came on the line from the British Embassy, and I said, \'93He\rquote 
s got to be got out, we can\rquote t deal with this here. We\rquote re not sure what it is. We think it\rquote s a kidney stone, and it\rquote s obviously not coming out, and so he needs proper medical care\'94. So they said, \'93
Well, we could send a helicopter\'94, and I said, \'93Yes, you\rquote d better do that\'94. And they said, \'93Who\rquote s going to pay?\'94 And I said, \'93SOAS will pay.\'94 (LAUGHS). You know, at that point, I just didn\rquote 
t care, because it was really scary! And it was the rainy season, which meant that even if we could get into Surkhet, and he would have to have been carried, there were no planes because the planes can\rquote 
t land in the rainy season, so it would have meant actually nine days walking into India, and I just thought that wasn\rquote t feasible. So, anyway, they did send, they sent a helicopter, with a medical 
student on board, and they all had to stay overnight because it was a small helicopter. And then the next day they took me down to Surkhet and left me on the airfield, and then they took Lionel to the hospital in Kathmandu, and then they came back for me 
- I can\rquote t quite remember exactly \endash 
 but anyway, we ended up at this hospital in Kathmandu, where Lionel was operated for a kidney stone. He was ill for a while. He had developed an infection after the operation. It was all a bit hair-raising! But anyway, he 
survived it and recovered, and eventually we thought he was well enough that we went back to the field, but we\rquote d obviously lost several weeks of fieldwork, which was very unfortu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451632 nate.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 So I decided, this time, I wasn\rquote t going to do what I\rquote 
d done in my previous village study, which was that I would know everything about everybody, but I was going to focus in on the things I\rquote d become interested in, which is what I did. So we were able to finish a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15930642 reasonable amount of fieldwork.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 Then when we 
left, at Thyssen House, we met some people there and we were talking about going back to the UK, and in those days, you could plan your route, your air route, in terms of mileage, so as long as the mileage stayed the same, it didn\rquote 
t matter which route you took. So we were saying to people, \'93Oh well, we\rquote re thinking about where we should go on the way home\'94, because we wanted to stop off for a short holiday, and somebody said, \'93Go to Madras, it\rquote 
s really nice. And here\rquote s a contact for you\'94. So that\rquote s what we did. We went to Madras - we flew from Kathmandu, probably via Delhi or Calcutta, I don\rquote 
t remember, and we flew down to Madras, and we looked up this contact, who worked for the Indian Tourist Board, very very nice and bright woman, who said, \'93Right. How long have you got? This is what you need to do \'85 blah, blah, blah\'94
. So she sent us to concerts of Indian music, and Madras in December is fantasti}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1015086 c, because it\rquote s what they call \lquote the season\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042  and it\rquote s the season of music and dance, and you could be at six all d
ay and all night if you wanted to. And she sent us to an ancient small well, it had been a city at one time, but there was just a temple left by then, called Mahalbalipuram,, which is south of Madras, a very famous, beautiful site, and several other sugge
stions that she made. And we just absolutely fell in love with it! We thought it was wonderful! So we thought, \'93Well, maybe next time this i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1015086 
s where we might like to come\'94.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 So when we got back to London, and I found out I was pregnant, and so we had Emma, o
ur daughter, later that year, and then our son two years later. And then two years after that \endash  in other words, four years after we\rquote d come back from Nepal \endash 
 it was time for Lionel to go again, to do fieldwork, and it had to be somewhere in South Asia, so we thought we\rquote d really like to go back to Madras, because we\rquote d liked it, and because we both wanted to do an urban study, because we\rquote 
d done all this rural fieldwork, and because we didn\rquote t want to take the children back to Nepal, because we thought it was too risky \endash  we didn\rquote t want them in helicopter rides in the middle of the monsoon! And we had a friend who
\rquote d lost a child in the hills in Nepal, and that had sort of scared us a bit. So that was what we did.
