Well, I did interviews, I did some participant observation, although not as much as I\rquote d done in the village in Mafia, because in the village in Mafia, I was there all the time,
 and I lived there, and slept there, and if I wanted to talk to somebody, I had to go and talk to somebody in Swahili and my entertainment, my leisure, everything was spent with people there. Whereas doing the fieldwork like that in Nepal was that I would
 go early in the morning, and I\rquote d come back just before it got dark, and I wasn\rquote 
t very often there in the evenings and overnight. And then because, at the beginning, at least, I needed an intermediary, and he was a male also, and the relations with women we
re not as free and easy as they had been in Tanzania. And obviously the language was also \endash  at the beginning, less so towards the end \endash 
 was an issue. But I did interviews, participant observation, lots of surveys of fields and households, later on. I mean, I knew from my previous Mafia experience that the survey work was better done late when people trusted you and knew who you were.

