 for example, from government service \endash  were the Brahmins, were the ones who sent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7354775  their kids to school, and the \lquote untouchables\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042  either couldn\rquote t, or didn\rquote t, or weren\rquote 
t allowed to in some instances. Most of them were illiterate, so they were very disadvantaged, not only in getting government jobs, but also in handling things like official forms, and I was told numerous stories of, \'93
Oh, they gave me this paper to sign, and I couldn\rquote t read it, so I just put my thumbprint, and found later on that, you know, the figures had all been falsified\'94, or \'93I\rquote d given away something I didn\rquote t intend to\'94}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1901704 . It was that kind of scenario.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
So as the government reach came more into these outlying areas - because this was a pretty remote area, the Far Western hills \endash  and the bureaucracy increa
sed, there were more openings for government jobs, which were mostly the preserve of the higher castes, and this also enabled them to engage, to use the money they were earning, in other ways, so that they would set up shops \endash 
 this is another thing that Lionel was looking at in the bazaars, these little bazaar shops, where they\rquote d sell cloth and things that people absolutely had to buy, because they couldn\rquote 
t produce them themselves. Some food, because not everybody was se}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7354775 lf-sufficient in food. And the \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 unto}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7354775 uchables\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042  didn\rquote 
t have access to those kind of ways of making money, so what they did, largely, was portering, and they would porter in goods from as far afield as India, on their backs, and bring them up over the mountains. So rice, they would bring from Su
rkhet, because there wasn\rquote t enough rice in the local area; the cloth that was sold in the bazaars would have been portered up. A porter, a Nepal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7354775 
ese porter, carries about an 80l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 b. load on his back, which is pretty heavy. Yeah. So they were making some money, but they weren\rquote 
t making enough money to deal with the fact that they couldn\rquote t support themselves because they hadn\rquote t got enough land, so they couldn\rquote t grow enough to feed themselves \endash  this is the lower castes I\rquote m talking now \endash 
 and much less to buy back land, because very often they\rquote 
d mortgaged their land. You see, this is the other thing, it was lending out money at exorbitant rates of interest, and then the mortgage being foreclosed, and people having to cede their land to those who had money \endash  the money
lenders. So that was another thing that people who had money, did with their money \endash  to turn it into more money \endash  was to lend out to people who didn\rquote 
t have money, but needed money desperately. If they had an illness or a wedding, or a funeral, they\rquote d have to find money, and they\rquote 
d have to agree to these very high rates of interest. So yes, so things had changed, and on the whole, you know, not necessarily for the better. So even though the place had opened up in certain respects, some people had done very w
