d trained together, and where all the men had been offered posts in the Department, you know, never mind applying, and being put up against competitors, it was just done very cosily in those days, so Lionel had got a job, and two or three other 
people, other males, and none of the females had been offered jobs. So when a job came up, I said to Christoph, \'93I\rquote m going to apply\'94, and he wrote me a letter and said I shouldn\rquote 
t do that, and he obviously felt very uncomfortable about it, but he made some excuse like, \'93You\rquote ve already published two books, and it will upset the seniority pecking order in the Department\'94. I mean, basically he didn\rquote 
t want a husband and wife in the Department, so that kind of ruled out \'85 So I think I\rquote d done the round - the LSE, that was where they asked me about motherhood. UCL, that was Mary Douglas. SOAS wouldn\rquote 
