\rquote t have an Anthropology Department at Goldsmiths\rquote , which was 
half in and half out of a university, it had a very anomalous status for a long time, and in those days, if you did a degree in certain subjects like psychology or geography, you have, in your first year, and could, in your second, if you wanted to, to do
 a subsidiary subject, so anthropology was there as a tame subsidiary subject for, first, psychology and then geography. And Goldsmiths\rquote 
, at that time, also ran both daytime full-time degrees, and evening part-time degrees, and there was one anthropologist teaching all these psychologists, and I don\rquote 
t know whether he had geographers when I first joined or not. But anyway, there were just too many, he couldn\rquote t handle them all. So they decided, finally, that they ought to have a second appointment. That was a 
guy called Brian Morris. And so it was the second post that I applied for, and I got it. So I started at Goldsmiths\rquote 
 in the autumn of 1977, and have been there ever since, more or less, with trips to the field, and a secondment to the School of Advanced Studies for three years, at one stage.
