\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab I suppose it\rquote s like, it\rquote s a bit like NGOs, isn\rquote t it, which is that you feel, on the one hand, \'93
Look, these are people who care. They\rquote re actually doing something. They recognise that there are lots of problems in the world, and they\rquote re seeking to address them in their own way\'94. And the other part of me thinks, \'93
This is not really the answer to anything, this is just a way of people either assuaging their consciences, or \'85\'94 Well, in the case of the women in Madras, it was very much a middle-class activity aimed at poorer people \endash  usually nameless 
\endash  and for whom services were provided that were determined from the top, not from the bottom. They didn\rquote t ask them, \'93Do you want this, that, or the other?\'94 \'93This is what we think is good for you\'94
, and often done in a very ritualistic way, so there would be presentations, very public presentatio
ns of clothing or food or whatever by the wealthy, who, of course, were always photographed and named, to the poor, who were always nameless - well, they might be in the photograph, but it would be as \'93a poor girl receives a dowry for her marriage\'94
 or something like that. So so I had quite mixed feelings about it, but I d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16258843 id make some very good friends.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 And then the organisations I mainly worked with were not the very top flight ones with the really upper class women, but I did get involved with some of tho
se, and that was very interesting, because that was very much of a studying up, and they really looked down on me because I had a paid job, which, of course, was - \'93Please!\'94 I mean, a paid job! And so they would either say, \'93She\rquote 
s a kind of social worker,\'94 they would say, \'93She\rquote s a paid social worker\'94
, which was considered very - they would sometimes call themselves social workers, but they meant voluntary, which was respectable, whereas being paid was definitely not. Or they would say, \'93Oh, her husband is from the University, and he\rquote 
s a professor of this, and she\rquote s come here with him\'94, so nobody really took what I was doing very seriously. And when I went back, I always remember giving a paper at SOAS once, where I talked about some of the political implicat
ions of this. Because what I actually discovered is that some of these women became extremely politically powerful, and that they had deliberately chosen the route to have political influence, not through the very dirty game of politics, as they saw it, w
here you can rapidly lose your reputation, but through this much more honourable route, as it was seen - as a social service, social welfare activities \endash 
 and this gave them access through the Indian Social Welfare Board, first as each state has its own Soci
al Welfare Board, and then India, as a whole, has a Social Welfare Board, and this gives you access to the very top levels of the Planning Commission and Parliament and the Cabinet and all the rest of it. And some women had actually made that jump, at tha
t stage, across into standing for election, or becoming co-opted members of some legislative body or another, and others of them had just stayed \'85
 I mean, there was one woman who ran a very powerful organisation in Madras, and when I first heard about her, and I asked who she was, I remember somebody saying to me, \'93Well, put it like this. The Governor \'85\'94 \endash 
 because each state has a Governor, who\rquote s the representative of the Delhi Government \endash  \'93The Governor phones her before he makes any important decision\'94. (L
AUGHS) So it was extremely interesting that these very demure-looking Indian women who had all this ideology as a good Hindu husband-worshipping wife, and who would constantly tell me, \'93Of course I have to be home, yes, I know we\rquote 
ve got a cook, but I have to serve him his supper. I have to be there. Actually, they were politicking, some of them, at the very highest level, so it was really a fascinating thing. And then also, in terms of what\rquote 
s going on today, what I could see in India was that the State was 
using these voluntary organisations as a cheap way of getting some form of social welfare without the need to actually do it, the State to take on board themselves. They could keep a lot of control, they could do it cheaply and it all sounded, you know, r
eally good. So they\rquote 
d give grants, the grants would come down from the top, from the Central, or the State Social Welfare Board, to these organisations, and, of course, they were fairly paltry, and so the organisations themselves had to fund-raise. Does thi
s all sound very familiar? Yeah. Exactly. That\rquote s what was going on.
