Well, I did. And, in fact, I think, right from the beginning, because I remember, before I sent in the application to the then SSRC for funding for this project, I went to see the - in those days, each officer was responsible for a particular discipline 
\endash  so I went to see the woman who was responsible for anthropology, to talk through the project with her, before I actually did the application, which is what you were supposed to do. And she read through my proposal, and then she said to me, \'93
I don\rquote t understand why you have to go to India to do this. Couldn\rquote t you do it just as well here?\'94 And, of course, the answer was that I could have done, with very similar sorts of findings, not just becau
se the British had been in India for so long and they\rquote d left their imprints \endash  because some of these organisations had been founded during the Colonial period, and it was the officers\rquote  wives, the British officers, the Colonial officers
\rquote  wives who\rquote d run welfare organisations of one kind or another, and then they\rquote d brought in Indian women, and then gradually, of course, the Indian women, themselves, took over \endash 
 so that was one reason. But also because I suppose welfare and charity is a very powerful way of masking power, a very good way of disg}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15688820 uising it.  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 And furthermore, in the situation in Madras, in those years, where a lot of people had come from somewhere else, and these women found themselves 
\endash  because of their husband\rquote s jobs \endash  living in the city, in a suburb, a growing metropolis, where they didn\rquote 
t have kin and family all around as they would have done in smaller towns or villages where their ancestors would have lived, they needed something to bring them together, and so social welfare was a very good wa
y of getting to know other people and socialisin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4470859 g, and finding out who was who.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 Because Madras, really, in those days, was like a village - I mean, I eventually had an almost complete map of who was who and what was what in that city, so even though it wa
s very large, the people who mattered, at the top, were a relatively small number, and they all knew each other and interacted, and this is one of the ways that the women interacted. The Neighbourhood Association was a little bit - I mean, they did that t
oo, but they also were very keen on, as they put it, \'93learning new things\'94
, and these were middle-class women kind of struggling to adapt to not only an urban environment, but a changing environment, and so they wanted to learn things like how to bake cakes \endash  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14175517 I think you probably read that.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
And, in fact, it was when I gave the seminar paper at SOAS soon after I\rquote d returned, and I mentioned the cake-making, and this guy absolutely expostulated, \'93My God! Are we going to sit here in a seminar and hear about cake-baking!\'94
 And, of course, I said, \'93Well!\'94 and in a later article I wrote something like - because somebody from LSE, which had several Indianists, had just published a book on \'93Burning ghats\'94
, where they burn the bodies, and the symbolism, and temples and stuff, and I said, \'93Why is cake-making less important than burning ghats, and temples?\'94 (LAUGHS) Because it has very heavy symbolic significance. It\rquote 
s a sign of modernity, and the cakes are used on certain particular kinds of occasions, and they involve using an oven, which most Indian kitchens, at that time, didn\rquote t have, so unless you had enough money to be able to purchase an oven, you couldn
\rquote t bake a cake. And then improving their English. I mean, I ran an English language discussion group for a long time, which was fantastic for me, because I\rquote d get them to talk about all sorts of things, you know, \'93Let\rquote 
s do mothers-in-law today\'94, and out would come all this stuff! And they would improve their English in the process. So they wanted to, you know, kind of establish their claims to modernity in a somewhat different way as well as the social welfare.

