\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid856940 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab Yes. Well, I think this has a long history. In 1975, before I got a job, a proper teaching job, I was feeling very despondent, because I
\rquote d applied for several jobs, and I hadn\rquote t got them, and even though I\rquote d published two books by then, I used to feel that two children cancelled out two books and that nobody was going to give 
me a job, and it was all very aggravating, and so when this offer came, that the Royal Anthropological Institute was making an anthropological series with the BBC, and they were going to shoot in five or six different societies, and would I like to be one
 of them, would I like Mafia to be one of them? Of course it was an offer that, you know, was hard to resist. So I agreed to go. And I rapidly realised that being a consultant actually had very little meaning, because you weren\rquote 
t consulted very often, and t
hat the kind of premises on which I lived my life in that village, and that they had come in [with] to shoot film, were completely different, and so we had an awful lot of arguments, and, in fact, it ended up with the most almighty row where I nearly walk
ed out. Because I thought that we should always negotiate permission to film, and we should ask people\rquote s consent, and they thought they just had the right to kind of stick their cameras in. And they didn\rquote 
t like the living conditions, they weren\rquote t used to living - whereas for me, I mean, I thought we lived quite well, actually! (LAUGHS) But I suppose I\rquote m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3698389  used to it! So it wasn\rquote t easy.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
Then when we came back and we did the editing, that was a huge job, and I didn\rquote t agree with a lot of the editing, and I had quite a few arguments about payment because they said they\rquote d paid me, and that that included everything that flowed 
\endash  the editing work, and the transcription of the sound recordings and writing the script, and I kept saying, \'93This is ridiculous, you spend so much money, and yet you won\rquote t give me anything, and this is a huge amount of work\'94
. Actually, it was quite funny on the transcription, because they said, \'93We\rquote re not going to pay you\'94, so I said, \'93Well, that\rquote s fine. I won\rquote t do them, then. Find somebody else to do them\'94. They said, \'93We\rquote 
ll find somebody else\'94. So they went to the BBC Swahili Service, and they got a guy who started working on them, and he couldn\rquote t do it, because there was some Mafia dialect in there, and there was a specialised vocabulary for
 spirit possession which he knew nothing whatsoever about! So they had to come back slightly tail between their legs, and say, \'93Yes, we\rquote ll }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid269957 
pay you to do it\'94. So I did it.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 And the actual way that the film series was constructed, Prince Charles was involved, it was called }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 Face Values}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
, and it was screened in 1977 or 1978, with a glossy book, coffee table book, to go with, and he did the linking interviews. He was the man in the street, well, he was actually man in Windsor Castle! (LAUGHS) So we had a very int
eresting day with him, in Windsor Castle, doing all these interviews, where he\rquote d ask us questions! (LAUGHS) Anyway, he did his best! And the thing was launched to much fanfare, and shown in a series of six or eight programmes \endash 
 I forget exactly how many. And to be very honest, they weren\rquote 
t fantastically good, as films, because in a real ethnographic film of the kind that was quite popular, that Granada Television showed quite a bit in those days, you did focus in on a particular place, and you learnt someth
ing about that place and those people there, whereas this was hopping around all over the place: from the Kayapo Indians in Brazil, to Malta, to Tanzania, to gypsies in California. It was a sort of Cook\rquote 
s Tour of what anthropology might do, and as one reviewer said, \'93This is a very interesting series, and it all went to show that people everywhere are the same, except when they\rquote re different\'94
, which just about summed it up! (LAUGHS) So I think the RAI and Prince Charles had thought this would be a great contribution to ethnic relations, and showing everybody that we\rquote re all the same underneath, even though we look very different, and I
\rquote m not sure to what extent it actually succeeded in that, but it was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid856940  a very interesting experience.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 But it was an experience w
here I felt I had absolutely no control, and so I suppose when it became possible, and there were camcorders, and they were light, and easy to operate, even for people without any training, like me, it was irresistible, wasn\rquote 
t it! So I bought a camcorder, I think I bought it at the airport - no, I did actually buy it a few days before I went to Tanzania in 2002, and I took a quick look at the manual, and had another quick look on the plane, and then I just shot. Some of it
\rquote s really poor, and some of it \'85 I think about 12 hours I came back with. And fortunately, Goldsmiths\rquote  has a very strong interest in visual anthropology, so there are students who have got technical training that I don\rquote 
t have, who know how to edit on a computer and all that sort of stuff, s
o I asked if any of the post-grads would like to work with me on this film, and I got a really nice, very bright, American student, called Carrie Clanton, and we did the film together. So she did all the editing. But she also made suggestions, and I said 
to her, \'93Carrie, your Swahili is improving every time we have an editing session!\'94 (LAUGHS) And she actually put it all together. And just as we finished the film, the news of Mikidadi\rquote 
s death came through, you know, my brother, and it was her idea, she put
 in an ending which makes me cry every time I see it, which is him sort of standing on the beach in the last time we were together, and I shot him throwing stones in the water. And then there\rquote 
s a thing comes over and says he died a few months later. And many times when I\rquote ve screened it, you hear people go, \'93Oooh!\'94 because he\rquote s appeared in the film, he\rquote s talking to kids in the Koran School, he\rquote 
s talking to young people in the Madrasa, he\rquote s talking to me about what have we done, what do we need to do? He\rquote s very much part of the work t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10108277 
hat we were doing at that time.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 So anyway I\rquote ve screened it to various people. I\rquote 
ve never shown it at an ethnographic film festival, because it\rquote s amateurish, I feel. I mean, she\rquote s done a very good job with what she could, but if you\rquote re going to shoot film, it\rquote 
s very hard to construct a film post facto, so there were whole sequences where there was a point I wanted to make, and in the middle I\rquote ve had to use stills, I\rquote ve got a big collection, but there just wasn\rquote t anything there in t
he way of film material. So if I were going to do it again, I suppose I would sit down and think, in advance, about exactly what it was that I wanted to get, if possible, and what I could do with it afterwards, and make sure that I\rquote 
d covered all the contingencies in the way that it wasn\rquote 
t possible there. But it was very satisfying to be holding the camera myself, and shooting what I wanted to shoot, and asking people and negotiating the whole thing. I enjoyed doing that. And then there was the website that kind of came on after that.

