\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10108277 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab It\rquote s been shown quite a number of times. The producer, at the end, he said to me, \'93I\rquote 
ve got the rushes. I can give you a copy of the rushes, with all the Mafia stuff all linked up together\'94. Because it was actually chopped into bits in some series that were shown, so there were some quite long sequences and some very short seq
uences. So the people in the village desperately wanted to see this film, and I was incredibly worried because there were some interviews that I knew people had only agreed to, in the film, because they were confidential, so nobody else was there when we 
shot those interviews, and they didn\rquote t mind people in Europe hearing what they were saying, but they didn\rquote t want people in the village to hear what they were saying. Very fortunately, it\rquote 
s got a magnetic soundtrack, which means that the sound doesn\rquote t appear when it\rquote s played on the projectors I\rquote 
d been able to get hold of on Mafia, which, as you can imagine, are pretty dicey anyway, with the generator and all the rest of it. But the last time I screened it, I screened a video on a television screen, and there were a thousand people watching a 14
\'94 television! (LAUGHS) And, of course, a lot of the people who appear in this film have died since then. But I\rquote ve sent lots of copies of the more recent film, the 2003 film, back to Tanzania, and people have seen it and 
lots of people know about it. In fact, I think it\rquote s been copied and copied and copied by anybody who can copy, so it\rquote s been}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10108277 
 fairly well distributed there.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 The most interesting screening I did was this village in Wales, where we spend a lot of time, which I\rquote 
ve known also for over 30 years. I screened it to them, to the people from the village, in the Community Centre, and tried to explain to them that they may be sheep farmers in Wales, and these are coconut farmers in Mafia, but the same kind of conversati
ons would be there, you know, \'93The weather\rquote s lousy\'94, \'93The crops are not getting enough money\'94, \'93Prices / inputs are going up\'94
, and so on and so forth. Anyway, they really enjoyed it. And the bit they particularly enjoyed was that I had taken a film, in Wel
sh, about Wales - I got it from S4C, the Welsh television channel - about sheep farming in Wales, and shown it when I showed the other film to the villagers in Mafia, who, of course, were completely entranced. And the thing that they thought was most wond
erful were the quad bikes, and they thought if they could have quad bikes to get around their coconuts! (LAUGHS) So it was a nice back and forth in that way. So I guess what I\rquote 
ve been trying to do in these later years, is to engage with a different audience. Well, not just an anthropology audience, to try to give back more, but also to engage with a wider audience, and try to show some of what anthropologists do, and what I
\rquote ve been doing. That\rquote s become quite important to me.
