\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
Well, I guess I arrived at a critical moment when they weren\rquote t really communicating any more, but they needed to communicate, and there was still a possibility that the relationship might be put back together, but then it wasn\rquote 
t. I think, sometimes, as an anthropologist, even one who\rquote s developed a very strong relationship, or close relationships with people, you\rquote re always going to retain some of your outsider
 status, and therefore people sometimes feel very safe talking about things that they wouldn\rquote t feel safe talking to other people that they\rquote 
ve got to carry on living with forever. And also, I always made it a point to try to preserve confidentiality. I would never say, \'93Well, I heard this from so and so\'94, I\rquote d say, \'93I\rquote ve heard such and such\'94. \'93Who told you that?
\'94 Of course, I\rquote m not going to say who told me that, because they told me in confidence. So I think, on the whole, people knew that I wouldn\rquote t break confidences. I don\rquote 
t know if other anthropologists had that experience. I really don\rquote t know. Anyway, the point is, the marriage did break up, and she eventually married somebody else after a very long time, and he never married, although he talked about it s
everal times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
