I suppose the thing is that in fieldwork, it\rquote s quite obvious, looking at what you say, each time you develop these very close relationships with quite a lot of people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
Well, if you keep going back over a period of nearly 45 years now, clearly - I remember the first time I went back, the thing that struck me most was that people, they said things like, \'93We thought you\rquote d never come back\'94, \'93We\rquote 
ve remembered you, and we\rquote ve thought about you, but we really didn\rquote t think you\rquote d come back. You\rquote ve gone off into that other world\'94. And now they know that I do come back - not that often, because it\rquote 
s difficult and expensive, and all the rest of it \endash  but I do come back. And I actually had a funny experience, it must have been about 2002, I was in the district capital, and I was with one of this man\rquote s (Mohammed) daughters \endash 
 the one I write about in the book. I forget what I call her now, but her name was Saidia, and somebody accosted her, and shouted across the road, \'93Oh, who\rquote s that person you\rquote re with? That European?\'94 And she said, and she }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10108277 used my Mafia name, which is \lquote Mama\rquote , it means \lquote woman\rquote  or \lquote Mrs\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042  Patlisha, because they}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10108277  find it very difficult to say \lquote Patricia\rquote , so 
\lquote Patlisha\rquote . \lquote Mama Patlisha\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 . And so the other person shouts back, \'93Well, how do you talk to her?\'94
 And she shouts back, \'93What do you mean, how do I talk to her?\'94 and she uses}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10108277  a word in Swahili which means \lquote our local person\rquote , \lquote 
our native person\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 , \'93and that\rquote s how I talk to her\'94. It was very suddenly a very nice feeling, because in Swahili there
\rquote s a very big distinction between a guest and a stranger, which is one category of people, and a local person who you know, and who knows you, and knows the area, because they\rquote re local \endash 
 and that was the word she used about me. So I guess I\rquote d become the anthropologist as native, kind of thing!}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10108277  \'93Gone native\'94}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042  as the British used to say! (LAUGHS)
