\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2122151 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab Well, I\rquote d been doing some 
work on the relationship between food, health and fertility, in Tanzania, and done a couple of trips around that, and for years I\rquote d been saying to my students \endash  as we all had, in the Anthropology Department \endash  \'93
You can do anthropology quite as well in Britain or Europe as you can somewhere further afield\'94. And then the ESRC had this research programme called \'93The Nation\rquote s Diet\'94, and the main question it asked was, \'93
Why do people eat what they do?\'94 And I thought, \'93Oh! I know quite a lot about food\'94. In fact, I started to teach a course on the Anthropology of Food, which I remember started as an Away Weekend at Goldsmiths\rquote 
: we were all supposed to give a little talk on something, and I thought, \'93Oh, I\rquote ll talk about food\'94. And at that time, when I gave that litt
le talk, there was very very little published, but there was some anthropological material, and lots of other material that could be incorporated. So anyway, eventually I set up an Anthropology of Food course at Goldsmiths\rquote 
, which ran for many years, and was quite successful, so when this ESRC thing was announced, I put in for it, and I got one of the awards to run a research project. What I was interested in \endash 
 this was a time when this was Thatcher still, and the government, I think, was really looking to 
find ways to reduce the health bill somewhat, and they wanted people to eat more healthily, so they gave tiny bits of money to the Health Education Council, and there\rquote 
d been a government - first a Green and then a White Paper about food and health, and the relationship between the two. So it was around as a policy issue, and I was interested in it as an anthropological issue, and I taught this course, so I}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid355689  knew the literature very well.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
So I constructed this project which was called, \'93Concepts of Healthy Eating\'94
, and what I was interested in was why was it that if there was all this information that the government and the Health Education Council were constantly putting out, and that the few studies that were available seemed to suggest people knew, they co
uld regurgitate, almost exactly, what the advice was, \'93Don\rquote t eat this\'94. \'93Do eat that\'94
, why was the diet, in Britain, getting worse and worse? Why was there growing obesity, diabetes, coronary heart disease, and all the rest of it? So it was a problem about
 rationality really, and all of the kind of rationality debates that there had been, so I guess t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2122151 hat was at the back of my mind.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 I decided that this had to be localised, and it would be easiest to do in the vicinity of Goldsmiths\rquote , which is an interesting
 vicinity because it has quite a mixed population, ethnically and class-wise, and it was near at hand, and I could get links, I could use a snowballing technique, because Goldsmiths\rquote 
 is there in the community. So, anyway, it was going to be a project I directed, because I was Head of Department at the time, and there was just no way \'85
 So we got two half-time Research Associates, and we split a post, and then the other half of their time they were registered as Ph.D. students. One of them did finish her Ph.D., and she now works for the BBC, and the other one, sadly, when she\rquote 
d got quite a long way, decided not to finish her Ph.D., and she went off and had two children. But anyway, the amount of data these two generated was phenomenal, and we developed all sor
ts of different methodologies. It was quite complex in terms of its methodology, because we didn\rquote 
t just use interviews which were taped and transcribed, but we also used food diaries and food frequency questionnaires. What else did we do? They did quite a lot of participant observation \endash 
 they went to Weight Watchers, and they went to this, that, and the other, and there was really quite a lot of that. And we looked at primarily white British and black British of West Indian origin, because there were West A
fricans, there were Vietnamese, there were just too many [ethnic groups in Lewisham], we decided we\rquote d just better keep it [to two]. They went to West Indian cookery classes, all sorts of stuff. And then they put it all on to \'93Nudist\'94
, which was a new package at that time - the \'93Nudist database system\'94 \'85 I think it\rquote s moved on now, and there\rquote s something else, the name of which I forget, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2122151 people aren\rquote t using Nudist now.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
Then the ESRC announced that this was going very well, and that they wanted there to be a s
econd round. So they had a second call for applications, and so I decided to put in, this time to do a completely different area, and I decided to choose West Wales, because I know it very well, and I thought there were some very interesting issues there.
 And I got that as well. So then we appointed another Research Associate, who is Welsh-speaking, and who trained as an anthropologist, she was a mature woman, middle-aged woman \'85
