Annie Keane. Yes. Annie had done her first degree with us, in anthropology and media studies, and I think the media thing still - well, she ended up at the BBC, as I\rquote ve told you. And Anna had done a Masters at University Col
lege. Anna, she did some really interesting work around issues like permaculture. In fact, what was amazing was we thought that the whole scene and the food and everything would be so different in Wales and Lewisham, but we kept finding unexpected overlap
s, like the permaculture: there were permaculture people in Wales, there were permaculture people in Lewisham. People ate goats in Wales, people ate - well, West Indians,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3685866  anyway, ate goats in Lewisham!  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
But it was the second project, we also got a project administrator [Karen Catling], which was a huge load off my shoulders, and she was absolutely brilliant. She\rquote d been an administrator at Goldsmiths\rquote , and then she\rquote 
d had to pull out for family reasons, and
 she was looking to kind of get back in, but nothing too onerous at that stage. So she worked on the projects for two years, and she was just brilliant. She was a tower of strength. She took all the administration off my shoulders and she kept everybody o
n speaking terms, and she even did some of the statistical analysis for us. She was really amazing! So anyway, finally the two projects finished, and we did all our reports, and we\rquote d done some publications. And what I had hoped, which, sadly, didn
\rquote t happen \'85
 the idea, when we first started, was that we would generate this database which any of us could - we could publish collectively, or in twos or threes, or singly, whatever, but all the other people went off to do other things. So I think Janice wrote one 
article after the projects had finished, and Annie finished her Ph.D., and that was that. Anna didn\rquote t do any more anthropology writing \endash 
 as far as I know. So it was kind of left with me! I was left holding this huge baby, or bath water or whatever! Anyway,
 there was a lot of it! And in the meanwhile, I was still keeping on with my Indian and my Tanzanian research, and so I did use, I did draw on it a bit. And I continued, every time I went back to Wales, I tried to keep tabs on certain things. Like the BSE
 thing I continued to monitor, and, of course, there\rquote d been other animal diseases since then. And now we\rquote re having bovine TB and badger culling in Wales, and I\rquote m writing about that.
