\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10501576 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab Yeah. It\rquote s a bit of a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10489256\charrsid12206042 
side-line}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042  really, it\rquote s not my major research interest. So I always felt very guilty. The ESRC said to me, at the end, \'93Well, now you
\rquote ve got to archive all this\'94, and, of course, it was in no fit shape to be archived, because they had just started their new archiving policy, which is that \'93if you get money from us, you\rquote ve got to archive\'94
. So it just sat around. And finally, after I retired, I decided this was something I was going to do, so I spent a whole summer working on it, and, of course, I had to reconstruct all the logic and th
e methods and all the rest of it, and put all the data together and catalogue it. Anyway, I did it. I had to anonymise all the Welsh data because we\rquote d never anonymised that. So it was a very big job, but I\rquote m very glad I did it. And so it
\rquote s all sa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10489256 fely lodged at ESDS [at Essex].  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
So I did a few of those interviews because, like you said before, if you haven\rquote t done some of them yourself, you really don\rquote t have a feel. But I always found it more difficult, using that data for writing, because I think at least ha
lf of what you write is what\rquote s in your head already, and, of course, not all of that data was in my head. And when we finished, we had 300 1-2 hour interviews on both projects, and I can\rquote 
t remember how many food diaries, and how many food frequency questionnaires and all the other stuff, there was a really massive amount of data. So even though I read everything as it came in, I can\rquote 
t pretend I remembered every single thing. It would have been very difficult. So I did one edited book where we all contribute
d articles and some other stuff as well, and we published quite a few articles and reports, but the monograph that I had always planned to write, in the end, I thought, \'93This is never going to happen. I\rquote 
m not going to sit down and be able to work through and with this mass of material that\rquote s not in my head\'94. So depositing it in the archive was a bit of a load off my shoulders really. I just hope that other people will use it, because I think it
\rquote s fantastic data. It\rquote s very very interesting, and it\rquote s a real snapshot of a moment in time where people talk about their ideas ab}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10501576 
out food, health, and the body.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 
But, of course, food leads you into so many other areas, which is one of the things I was saying in the paper on archiving that I did, that I actually edited
 some of the interviews, and I took out sections because some of them were too intimate, and people might have been recognisable, because when you talk about food, you get into the most intimate aspects of peoples\rquote  lives \endash 
 their childhood, their sex lives, you name it - what they feel about the world, and themselves, is encapsulated in food. So it\rquote s a wonderful topic to work with, really really interesting. And, of course, everybody\rquote 
s got something to say about food! So you never have an interview where people gum up because everybody eats it and and uses it.
