\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab 
From listening to you, I get the feeling that the main problem of working with material that other people have collected, is really it\rquote s not sufficiently in your head - or is there something deep
er, that you have a kind of relationship when you know the person, or an interview when you did it yourself. What do you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12206042\charrsid12206042 Pat:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14303659\charrsid12206042 \tab I suppose it\rquote 
s a kind of feeling of ownership, isn\rquote t it. \'93This is my data\'94, whereas when you\rquote re getting it second-hand, no matter how good it is. I mean, on the whole, they were all good fieldworkers, and they did their work well, but it doesn
\rquote t have the same immediacy. You weren\rquote t there, you didn\rquote t see, you didn\rquote t smell, you didn\rquote t hear this voice of the person speaking, so it isn\rquote t quite the same. The Welsh data is more immediate for me, because I
\rquote m so familiar with that community, so even though I didn\rquote t know all of the people concerned, I know the background, I know the culture. I don\rquote t know whether it ever would be possible to work entirely with somebody else\rquote 
s material and produce something totally convincing, and I think that has to do with the reaction that I told you about, when I gave the seminar on archiving at SOAS, and they said, \'93No way!\'94 None of them would agree to archiving. \'93
This is very personal to me, and I don\rquote t want other people to see it\'94. \'93I\rquote ll publish, because then I\rquote m in control, and I can decide what other people see and don\rquote t see, but not the raw data\'94. That\rquote s, I think, wh
